TextChange: Should materialism be a criticism of modern society?\nThough ladies enjoy shopping for clothing and shoes, have you ever seen a woman who is content simply because she has everything she desires? As a result, materialism should be critiqued for at least three reasons. To begin with, it is misinterpreted as a means of achieving true happiness. Anyone who knows Mother Teresa knows that love is the key to happiness. People find tranquilly and fulfilment via love, but a craving for material things leads to an ongoing cycle of appeal. Many affluent people, such as Bill Gates, Jackie Chen, and Michael Jackson, who devote themselves to philanthropy, can attest to this. Second, materialism skews the definition of material.

It exists to better our lives by providing our basic requirements and allowing us to grow. My grandfather always claims that when he was younger, he had considerably fewer recreational opportunities than I do now, but that people were happier back then because life was simpler and easier. To make money, people today sacrifice everything, including their health. What a bunch of idiots.\n\nLast but not least, accumulating wealth and spending money deprives people of their ability to experience love, care, and other pleasant emotions. Families disintegrate, schoolmates no longer have fun together, and even married couples rarely communicate. Is it healthy to put so much on the line in order to be materialistic? In every manner, I have my doubts.
